On 1/11/2002 at 11:05 AM Magnus ?or Torfason wrote:
I have an XML generation process that I use to convert internal
datastructures to XML.  I want this process to be Unit tested, to
ensure
that the generated XML matches the template XML that I have defined.

My problem is that the only way to compare the two files in a simple
way is
to do a string compare.  This is not acceptable, since I am not
interested
in string equality (encoding and linefeed may very well differ) but in
XML
equality (that both documents have exactly the same elements and
attributes).

Does anyone know of a way to compare two XML files so that only the XML
semantics are compared, not the underlying strings?
I haven&#39;t tried it before, but if the DOM object model implements
equals correctly, then you should be able to parse both files and ask
whether the root Node objects are equal.

If that doesn&#39;t work, then you should be able to write a simple
recursive algorithm that does the equals comparison the way you&#39;d want.
Something like &quot;XmlUtil.assertXmlDocumentsEquals()&quot; which takes two
root Node objects and walks the respective trees. I&#39;m not sure how
complex that would be.
